00:29:38.512 --> 00:29:41.492
then you have to... Okay, then you get through that loop, then you have to

510
00:29:43.372 --> 00:29:46.872
contact them and let them decide whether they want

511
00:29:47.812 --> 00:29:48.412
the result.

512
00:29:49.672 --> 00:29:53.632
And we actually had a long discussion, interesting, with our community advisory

513
00:29:53.712 --> 00:29:57.592
board about... They said, "Well, why are you only returning

514
00:29:57.602 --> 00:30:01.452
actionable results? What if I just want to know?" Somebody said, "I want to

515
00:30:01.512 --> 00:30:04.532
pray on it." And it's like, I never thought of that.

516
00:30:04.572 --> 00:30:07.112
We still kept it in the clinical actionable,

517
00:30:08.032 --> 00:30:11.472
but not returned in their medical... First they have to decide, do I want to know?

518
00:30:11.922 --> 00:30:15.552
And then we actually had chatbots to help them walk through that because

519
00:30:15.932 --> 00:30:19.712
suddenly we've got thousands of people in a short time to interact

520
00:30:19.772 --> 00:30:22.492
with. Then they could get to a genetic counselor.

521
00:30:23.252 --> 00:30:27.092
I don't know if your institution, but genetic counselors are hard to find.

522
00:30:27.152 --> 00:30:31.072
There's not many of them. And then, so they can make the

523
00:30:31.112 --> 00:30:35.042
decision then if they wanted to do it, we replicated the

524
00:30:35.092 --> 00:30:38.692
result, still as a research result on their original blood

525
00:30:38.792 --> 00:30:39.172
sample.

526
00:30:40.612 --> 00:30:44.512
And then based on that, recommended they should go

527
00:30:44.572 --> 00:30:46.272
and hook them up with a clinical

528
00:30:47.172 --> 00:30:50.152
parallel result. So it's been a long process.

529
00:30:51.552 --> 00:30:54.708
There's been some people thatProbably.

530
00:30:55.208 --> 00:30:57.657
I don't know if it saved their life, but a few of them

531
00:30:59.108 --> 00:31:02.248
had been on diagnostic odysseys their whole life.

532
00:31:02.268 --> 00:31:06.108
They got the result back and went in, and their whole family got worked up.

533
00:31:06.148 --> 00:31:06.848
And they're like--

534
00:31:07.968 --> 00:31:11.778
It was life-changing for them. Those are anecdotes, and epidemiologists, we're

535
00:31:11.828 --> 00:31:13.188
very careful about anecdotes.

536
00:31:14.308 --> 00:31:18.128
So it's a tough call. We decided to put it all under research

537
00:31:18.208 --> 00:31:18.668
because

538
00:31:19.588 --> 00:31:23.048
as now that we can sequence the whole genome, this is only going to become a bigger

539
00:31:23.168 --> 00:31:26.888
issue. And so we need to learn how people can engage and want to find out

540
00:31:26.948 --> 00:31:30.848
results and move on with them. But it's almost a whole research

541
00:31:31.648 --> 00:31:32.948
thing in and of itself-

542
00:31:33.008 --> 00:31:33.228
Mm. Yeah

543
00:31:33.548 --> 00:31:35.848
... beyond just the cohorts doing their work.

544
00:31:35.898 --> 00:31:38.668
And I don't know that we have the resources to do this

545
00:31:40.088 --> 00:31:44.028
globally. So no easy

546
00:31:44.048 --> 00:31:44.908
answers on that one.

547
00:31:45.488 --> 00:31:46.568
Exactly.

548
00:31:46.648 --> 00:31:46.728
Ping.

549
00:31:46.968 --> 00:31:50.248
So if you're interested in this area,

550
00:31:51.668 --> 00:31:55.408
you can also look at See All Of Us, how they return the

551
00:31:55.468 --> 00:31:55.688
data.

552
00:31:56.108 --> 00:31:56.388
Mm.

553
00:31:56.448 --> 00:31:58.148
They're actually doing a very good job.

554
00:31:59.088 --> 00:32:00.088
So they return

